# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: datacenter-fabric
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-network-architectures] A **data center** is a pool of resources (computational, storage, network) interconnected using a communication network.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-network-architectures] A data center network (DCN) holds a pivotal role in a data center, as it interconnects all of the data center resources together.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-network-architectures] DCNs need to be scalable and efficient to connect tens or even hundreds of thousands of servers to handle the growing demands of cloud computing.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-network-architectures] Today's data centers are constrained by the interconnection network.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-network-architectures] The adoption of hybrid cloud computing has influenced the design of modern data center networks.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-network-architectures] By integrating on-premises infrastructure with private and public cloud environments, organizations can distribute applications and workloads across multiple locations.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-network-architectures] As a result, data center resources no longer need to be physically co-located and can communicate through interconnected network architectures.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-network-architectures] Data center networks can be divided into multiple separate categories.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-network-architectures] The legacy three-tier DCN architecture follows a multi-rooted tree based network topology composed of three layers of network switches, namely access, aggregate, and core layers.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-network-architectures] The servers in the lowest layers are connected directly to one of the edge layer switches.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-network-architectures] The aggregate layer switches interconnect together multiple access layer switches.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-network-architectures] All of the aggregate layer switches are connected to each other by core layer switches.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-network-architectures] Core layer switches are also responsible for connecting the data center to the Internet.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-network-architectures] The three-tier is the common network architecture used in data centers.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-network-architectures] However, three-tier architecture is unable to handle the growing demand of cloud computing.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-network-architectures] The higher layers of the three-tier DCN are highly oversubscribed.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-network-architectures] Moreover, scalability is another major issue in three-tier DCN.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-network-architectures] Major problems faced by the three-tier architecture include, scalability, fault tolerance, energy efficiency, and cross-sectional bandwidth.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-network-architectures] The three-tier architecture uses enterprise-level network devices at the higher layers of topology that are very expensive and power hungry.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-network-architectures] The fat tree DCN architecture reduces the oversubscription and cross section bandwidth problem faced by the legacy three-tier DCN architecture.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-network-architectures] Fat tree DCN employs commodity network switches based architecture using Clos topology.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-network-architectures] The network elements in fat tree topology also follows hierarchical organization of network switches in access, aggregate, and core layers.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-network-architectures] However, the number of network switches is much larger than the three-tier DCN.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-network-architectures] The architecture is composed of *k* pods, where each pod contains, (k/2)2 servers, k/2 access layer switches, and k/2 aggregate layer switches in the topology.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-network-architectures] The core layers contain (k/2)2 core switches where each of the core switches is connected to one aggregate layer switch in each of the pods.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-network-architectures] The fat tree topology can offer up to 1:1 oversubscription ratio and full bisection bandwidth, depending on each rack's total bandwidth versus the bandwidth available at the tree's highest levels.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-network-architectures] Higher tree branches are typically oversubscribed to their lower branches by a ratio of 1:5, with the problem compounding at the highest tree levels, including up to 1:80 or 1:240, at the highest levels.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-network-architectures] The fat tree architecture uses a customized addressing scheme and routing algorithm.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-network-architectures] The scalability is one of the major issues in fat tree DCN architecture and maximum number of pods is equal to the number of ports in each switch.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-network-architectures] DCell is a server-centric hybrid DCN architecture where one server is directly connected to one server.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-network-architectures] A server in the DCell architecture is equipped with multiple network interface cards (NICs).
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-network-architectures] The DCell follows a recursively built hierarchy of cells.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-network-architectures] A cell0 is the basic unit and building block of DCell topology arranged in multiple levels, where a higher level cell contains multiple lower layer cells.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-network-architectures] The cell0 is building block of DCell topology, which contains *n* servers and one commodity network switch.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-network-architectures] The network switch is only used to connect the server within a cell0.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-network-architectures] A cell1 contains *k=n+1* cell0 cells, and similarly a cell2 contains k * n + 1 dcell1.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-network-architectures] The DCell is a highly scalable architecture where a four level DCell with only six servers in cell0 can accommodate around 3.26 million servers.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-network-architectures] Besides very high scalability, the DCell architecture depicts very high structural robustness.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-network-architectures] However, cross section bandwidth and network latency is a major issue in DCell DCN architecture.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-network-architectures] Some of the other well-known DCNs include BCube, Camcube, FiConn, Jelly fish, and Scafida.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-network-architectures] A qualitative discussion of different DCNs along with benefits and drawbacks associated with each one has been made available.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-network-architectures] Scalability is one of the foremost challenges to the DCNs.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-network-architectures] With the advent of cloud paradigm, data centers are required to scale up to hundreds of thousands of nodes.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-network-architectures] Besides offering immense scalability, the DCNs are also required to deliver high cross-section bandwidth.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-network-architectures] Current DCN architectures, such as three-tier DCN offer poor cross-section bandwidth and possess very high over-subscription ratio near the root.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-network-architectures] Fat tree DCN architecture delivers 1:1 oversubscription ratio and high cross section bandwidth, but it suffers from low scalability limited to *k*=total number of ports in a switch.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-network-architectures] DCell offers immense scalability, but it delivers very poor performance under heavy network load and one-to-many traffic patterns.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-network-architectures] A quantitative analysis of the three-tier, fat tree, and DCell architectures for performance comparison (based on throughput and latency) is performed for different network traffic pattern.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-network-architectures] The fat tree DCN delivers high throughput and low latency as compared to three-tier and DCell.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-network-architectures] DCell suffers from very low throughput under high network load and one to many traffic patterns.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-network-architectures] One of the major reasons for DCell's low throughput is very high over subscription ratio on the links that interconnect the highest level cells.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-network-architectures] The DCell exhibits very high robustness against random and targeted attacks and retains most of its node in the giant cluster after even 10% of targeted failure. multiple failures whether targeted or random, as compared to the fat tree and three-tier DCNs.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-network-architectures] One of the major reasons for high robustness and connectivity of the DCell is its multiple connectivity to other nodes that is not found in fat tree or three-tier architectures.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-network-architectures] The concerns about the energy needs and environmental impacts of data centers are intensifying.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-network-architectures] Energy efficiency is one of the major challenges of today's information and communications technology (ICT) sector.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-network-architectures] The networking portion of a data center is accounted to consume around 15% of overall cyber energy usage.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-network-architectures] Around 15.6 billion kWh of energy was utilized solely by the communication infrastructure within the data centers worldwide in 2010.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-network-architectures] The energy consumption by the network infrastructure within a data center is expected to increase to around 50% in data centers.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-network-architectures] IEEE 802.3az standard has been standardized in 2011 that make use of adaptive link rate technique for energy efficiency.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-network-architectures] Moreover, fat tree and DCell architectures use commodity network equipment that is inherently energy efficient.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-network-architectures] Workload consolidation is also used for energy efficiency by consolidating the workload on few devices to power-off or sleep the idle devices.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] A **data center** is a facility used to house computer systems and associated components, such as telecommunications and storage systems.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Data centers are critical infrastructure for the storage and processing of information, and they support the global financial system, cloud services, machine learning, and artificial intelligence (AI).
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Data centers vary widely in terms of size, power and water requirements, and overall structure.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Hyperscale and colocation facilities collectively account for approximately 74% of U.S. server energy consumption as of 2023, a share that has grown significantly over the past decade as workloads have migrated away from enterprise on-premises infrastructure.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Since IT operations are crucial for business continuity, a data center generally includes redundant or backup components.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Other important design considerations are power supply, network infrastructure, environmental controls (e.g., cooling, fire suppression), and various measures for physical and data security.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Large data centers operate at an industrial scale, requiring significant energy.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Estimated global data center electricity consumption in 2024 was around 415 terawatt hours (TWh), or about 1.5% of global electricity demand.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] The International Energy Agency (IEA) projects that data center electricity consumption could double by 2030.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] The rapid growth of data center infrastructure has prompted regulatory debates in multiple jurisdictions regarding tax incentives, electricity grid impacts, water consumption, and compatibility with state and national climate commitments.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Rapid growth of the AI industry is leading to strain on electric grids and increased electricity costs for consumers.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] This in turn has drawn growing opposition to new data centers from local people who would bear the burdens of social and environmental impacts, such as energy and water use, while faraway actors and institutions would receive the projects' benefits.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] These opposition movements have materialized especially in parts of Europe, the U.S., and South America.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Billions of dollars in projects were halted or delayed by data center resistances in the U.S. between May 2024 and June 2025.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Data centers are usually classified according to their ownership model, scale, and intended use.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] However, these classifications are not mutually exclusive from each other, and they may overlap depending on the operational structure and service model of the particular data center.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Enterprise data centers are owned and operated by a single organization for their own internal information technology (IT) needs, rather than for commercial hosting of other companies' data.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] They used to be essential infrastructures; as in 2014, enterprise data centers accounted for over 60% of the U.S. server energy consumption, but this share fell sharply to about 10% by 2023 as workloads migrated to hyperscale and colocation facilities.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Energy efficiency at an enterprise data center tends to be significantly lower than at hyperscale facilities due to its cooling, which can account for over 30% of electricity consumption at enterprise sites, compared to roughly 7% at efficient hyperscale data centers.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] The shift away from enterprise facilities toward cloud and colocation infrastructure is one of the defining structural trends of the previous decade.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Colocation centers provide shared physical infrastructure, such as power, cooling, space, etc., to multiple tenants who lease space rather than building their own facilities.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Colocation data centers reduce expenditure for organizations while enabling operators to achieve economies of scale in power procurement and cooling efficiency.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Some of the largest data centers in the world are colocation centers, and this category accounted for about 22% of worldwide data center capacity as of 2024, making them the second-largest category by capacity after hyperscale facilities.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Major colocation providers include Equinix, Switch, COPT, and Digital Realty, which operate facilities across multiple continents.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Hyperscale data centers are large-scale facilities, typically exceeding 100 megawatts of power capacity, designed to support massive, scalable computing workloads for cloud services, AI training, and large-scale data processing.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] By the end of 2024, there were 1,136 operational hyperscale data centers globally, a figure that doubled over the previous five years, with the U.S. accounting for approximately 54% of total hyperscale capacity.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] In particular, the three largest operators, Amazon Web Services, Microsoft Azure, and Google Cloud, collectively account for approximately 59% of all hyperscale data center capacity globally.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] As a growing trend, hyperscale data centers represented about 41% of worldwide data center capacity in 2024 and are projected to exceed 60% by 2029 as enterprise on-premises infrastructure continues to decline.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Moreover, as artificial intelligence (AI) is becoming widely used, AI data centers are being built more rapidly, and they can consume as much electricity as 100,000 households, more than conventional data centers.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Since 2024, there has been widespread grassroots Opposition to AI Data Centers.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Edge data centers are smaller facilities, typically ranging from 1 to 10 megawatts.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] They are positioned closer to end users or data sources to reduce network latency and support real-time applications, such as autonomous vehicles, industrial automation, and content delivery.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Unlike hyperscale data centers, edge data centers are intentionally distributed across many locations rather than consolidated, with deployments occurring in urban areas, cell tower sites, as well as industrial locations.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] The growth of edge computing infrastructure has been tied to the expansion of 5G wireless networks and the increasing use of Internet of Things (IoT) devices, which generate data that is more efficiently processed near its source than transmitted to a centralized data center.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Micro data centers (MDCs) are access-level data centers that are smaller in size than traditional data centers but provide the same features.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] They are typically located near the data source to reduce communication delays, as their small size allows several MDCs to be spread out over a wide area.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] MDCs are suited to user-facing, front end applications.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] They are commonly used in edge computing and other areas where low latency data processing is needed.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Modularity and flexibility are key elements in allowing a data center to grow and change over time.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Data center modules are pre-engineered, standardized building blocks that can be configured and moved as needed.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] A modular data center may consist of data center equipment contained within shipping containers or similar portable containers.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Components of the data center can be prefabricated and standardized, which facilitates moving if needed.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] These modular data centers are useful for IT disaster recovery.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Mobile data centers are also used to move large quantities of data, by physically transporting the hardware that contains it, and in cryptocurrency mining, where fleets of mobile data centers are transported to take advantage of cheaper sources of energy.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Data centers have their roots in the huge computer rooms of the 1940s, typified by the Electronic Numerical Integrator and Computer (ENIAC), one of the earliest examples of a data center.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Early computer systems were complex to operate and maintain, and required a special environment in which to operate.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Many cables were necessary to connect all of the components, and methods to accommodate and organize these were devised such as standard racks to mount equipment, raised floors, and cable trays (installed overhead or under the elevated floor).
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] A single mainframe required a great deal of power and had to be cooled to avoid overheating.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Security became important – computers were expensive, and were often used for government and military purposes.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] As such, basic design guidelines for controlling access to the computer room were devised.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] During the microcomputer industry boom of the 1980s, computers started to be deployed everywhere, in many cases with little or no care about operating requirements.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] However, as information technology (IT) operations started to grow in complexity, organizations grew aware of the need to control IT resources.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] The availability of inexpensive networking equipment, coupled with new standards for the network structured cabling, made it possible to use a hierarchical design that put servers in a specific room inside the company.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] The use of the term *data center*, as applied to specially designed computer rooms, started to gain popular recognition about this time.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] During the dot-com bubble (1997–2000), there was a boom in data center construction because companies needed fast Internet connectivity and non-stop operation to establish their Internet presence.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] The global data center market saw steady growth in the 2010s, with a notable acceleration in the latter half of the decade.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] According to Gartner, worldwide data center infrastructure spending reached $200 billion in 2021, representing a 6% increase from 2020 despite economic challenges posed by the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] In 2024, global energy consumption from data centers was 620 TWh, with 80% of that consumption concentrated in the U.S., China, and the United Kingdom.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Colocation centers were the most common category worldwide, with 4,799 colocation centers in 127 countries.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] In that year, the largest data center in the world was Citadel, owned by Switch, at the Tahoe Reno Industrial Center in Reno, Nevada, occupying 7.2 million square feet.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Growth of the data center industry has prompted local resistance.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] A 2023 survey found social mobilizations against the industry in Europe, the U.S., and South America.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] These movements expressed concern about the centers' energy and water use, pollution, and impact on agriculture or the landscape.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] A 2026 poll by *Politico* suggested that resistance to growth of the industry would make candidates' stance on data centers a significant issue for voters in the U.S.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] The U.S. hosted 5,381 data centers in March 2024, the highest number of any country worldwide, accounting for 40% of the global market in 2023.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] As of 2023, about 80% of U.S. data center load was concentrated in 15 states, led by Virginia and Texas.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] As of 2025, roughly one third of America's data centers were in three states: Virginia (643), Texas (395), and California (319).
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] The largest concentration of data centers in the world is in Northern Virginia, with over 250 facilities in the region.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] In 2025, Georgia was the fastest growing data center hub in the U.S., having enacted several state tax exemptions for the industry and hosting between 100 and 150 centers in the state.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Local governments have responded to the growing industry in Georgia with a variety of local ordinances to guide permitting of these facilities.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] The consultancy firm McKinsey & Co., projected U.S. demand to double to 35 gigawatts (GW) by 2030, up from 17 GW in 2022.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] A study published by the Electric Power Research Institute (EPRI) in May 2024 estimated that data centers could consume between 4.6% and 9.1% of the country's electricity generation by 2030.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] GDP growth was only 0.1% without the investments in data centers for artificial intelligence.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Data centers house critical computing resources in a controlled environment and must generally operate with very high availability.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Key design elements include providing power for the equipment, temperature and humidity control, cabling, fire safety, and security.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] For this reason, a data center has to offer a secure environment that minimizes the chances of a security breach.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Industry research company International Data Corporation (IDC) puts the average age of a data center at nine years old.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Gartner, another research company, says data centers older than seven years are obsolete.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] The growth in data (163 zettabytes by 2025) is one factor driving the need for data centers to modernize.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Rapid obsolescence of data center equipment was a concern by at least 2007, and in 2011, Uptime Institute was concerned about aging equipment.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] The topology proposed in this document is intended to be applicable to any size data center.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Telcordia GR-3160, *NEBS Requirements for Telecommunications Data Center Equipment and Spaces*, provides guidelines for data center spaces within telecommunications networks, and environmental requirements for the equipment intended for installation in those spaces.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] These criteria were developed jointly by Telcordia and industry representatives.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] They may be applied to data center spaces housing data processing or IT equipment.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Power supplies, either back up or continuous onsite power, consist of one or more uninterruptible power supplies, battery banks, diesel, gas turbine, and/or gas engine generating sets.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Greater primary fuel energy efficiency can be achieved with the use of cogeneration technology, generating electricity, heating, and cooling onsite.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] To prevent single points of failure, all elements of the electrical systems, including backup systems, are typically given redundant copies, and critical servers are connected to both the *A-side* and *B-side* power feeds.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] This arrangement is often made to achieve N+1 redundancy in the systems.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Static transfer switches are sometimes used to ensure instantaneous switchover from one supply to the other in the event of a power failure.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Options for low-voltage cable routing might include data cabling that is routed through overhead cable trays; raised floor cabling, both for security reasons and to avoid the extra cost of cooling systems over the racks; and anti-static tiles for flooring, especially in low-cost data centers.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Maintaining suitable temperature and humidity levels is critical to preventing equipment damage caused by overheating.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Overheating can cause components (usually the silicon or copper of the wires or circuits) to melt, causing loose connections and fire hazards.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Typical temperature control methods include air conditioning and indirect cooling, such as the use of outside air, indirect evaporative cooling units, and seawater cooling.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Airflow management is the practice of achieving data center cooling efficiency by preventing the recirculation of hot exhaust air and by reducing bypass airflow.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Common approaches include hot-aisle/cold-aisle containment and the deployment of in-row cooling units, which position cooling directly between server racks to intercept exhaust heat before it mixes with room air.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Humidity control prevents moisture and related issues.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] For example, excess humidity can cause dust to adhere more readily to fan blades and heat sinks, impeding air cooling and leading to higher temperatures.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Cold aisle containment is done by exposing the rear of equipment racks, while the fronts of the servers are enclosed with doors and covers.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] This is similar to how large-scale food companies refrigerate and store products.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Computer cabinets/server farms are often organized for containment of hot/cold aisles.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Proper air duct placement prevents cold and hot air from mixing.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Rows of cabinets are paired to face each other so the cool and hot air intakes and exhausts do not mix air, which would severely reduce cooling efficiency.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Alternatively, a range of underfloor panels can create efficient cold air pathways directed to the raised-floor vented tiles.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Either the cold aisle or the hot aisle can be contained.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Another option is fitting cabinets with vertical exhaust duct chimneys.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Hot exhaust pipes/vents/ducts can direct the air into a plenum space above a dropped ceiling and back to the cooling units or to outside vents.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] With this configuration, traditional hot/cold aisle configuration is not required.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Data centers feature fire protection systems, including passive and active design elements, as well as implementation of fire prevention programs in operations.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Smoke detectors are usually installed to provide early warning of a fire.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Although the main room usually does not allow wet pipe-based systems due to the fragile nature of circuit boards, there are systems that can be used in the rest of the facility or in cold/hot aisle air circulation systems that are closed systems.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] These include sprinkler systems and misting, the latter of which uses high pressure to create extremely small water droplets and can be used in sensitive rooms due to the nature of the droplets.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] However, there are other means to put out fires, especially in Sensitive areas, usually using gaseous fire suppression, of which Halon gas was the most popular, until the negative effects of producing and using it were discovered.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Physical access to data centers is usually restricted.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Layered security often starts with fencing, bollards, and mantraps.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Video camera surveillance and permanent security guards are almost always present if the data center is large or contains sensitive information.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Fingerprint recognition is starting to become commonplace.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Logging access is required by some data protection regulations; some organizations tightly link this to access control systems.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Multiple log entries can occur at the main entrance, entrances to internal rooms, and at equipment cabinets.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Access control at cabinets can be integrated with intelligent power distribution units, so locks are networked through the same appliance.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Data center transformation takes a step-by-step approach through integrated projects carried out over time.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] This differs from a traditional method of data center upgrades, which takes a serial and siloed approach.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Typical projects within a data center transformation initiative include standardization/consolidation, virtualization, automation, and security.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Data center consolidation consists of reducing the number of data centers and avoiding *server sprawl* (both physical and virtual), which often includes replacing aging data center equipment.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] This process is aided by standardization, which makes these systems follow a uniform set of configurations to simplify and improve efficiency.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Automating tasks such as provisioning, configuration, patching, release management, and compliance are other ways in which data centers can be upgraded.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] These changes are needed not just when facing fewer skilled IT workers.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Lastly, security initiatives integrate the protection of virtual systems with existing security for physical infrastructures.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] The first raised floor computer room was made by IBM in 1956 to allow access for wiring.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] During the 1970s, raised floors became more common because they allow cool air to circulate more efficiently.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] A raised floor standards guide (GR-2930) was developed by Telcordia Technologies, a subsidiary of Ericsson.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] The "lights-out" data center, also known as a darkened or dark data center, is a data center that has largely eliminated the need for direct access by personnel, except under extraordinary circumstances.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Due to the lack of need for staff to enter the data center, it can be operated without lighting.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] All of the devices are accessed and managed by remote systems, with automation programs used to perform unattended operations.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] In addition to the energy savings, reduction in staffing costs, and the ability to locate the site further from population centers, implementing a lights-out data center also reduces the threat of malicious attacks upon the infrastructure.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA) regulations require monitoring of noise levels inside data centers if noise exceeds 85 decibels.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] The average noise level in server areas of a data center may reach as high as 92–96 dB(A).
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Residents living near data centers have described the sound as "a high-pitched whirring noise 24/7", saying "It's like being on a tarmac with an airplane engine running constantly ...
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] External sources of noise include HVAC (heating, ventilation, and air conditioning) equipment and energy generators.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Location factors include proximity to power grids, telecommunications infrastructure, networking services, transportation lines, and emergency services.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Other considerations should include flight paths, neighboring power drains, geological risks, and climate (associated with cooling costs).
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Local political considerations, such as availability of subsidies and lack of opposition, are also important factors in locating data centers.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Various metrics exist to measure the data-availability that results from data-center availability beyond 95% uptime, with the top of the scale counting how many *nines* can be placed after *99%*.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] The costs of avoiding downtime should not exceed the cost of the downtime itself.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Dynamic infrastructure provides the ability to intelligently, automatically, and securely move workloads within a data center anytime, anywhere, for migrations, provisioning, to enhance performance, or build co-location facilities.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] It also facilitates performing routine maintenance on either physical or virtual systems, all while minimizing interruption.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] A related concept is Composable Infrastructure, which allows for the dynamic reconfiguration of the available resources to suit needs, only when needed.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Communications in modern data centers are most often based on networks running the Internet protocol suite.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Data centers contain a set of routers and switches that transport traffic between the servers and to the outside world, which are connected according to the data center network architecture.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Redundancy of the internet connection is often provided by using two or more upstream service providers (see Multihoming).
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Some of the servers at a data center are used for running the basic internet and intranet services needed by internal users in the organization, e.g., e-mail servers, proxy servers, and DNS servers.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Network security elements are also usually deployed: firewalls, VPN gateways, intrusion detection systems, and so on.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Also common are monitoring systems for the network and some of the applications.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Additional off-site monitoring systems are also typical, in case of a failure of communications inside the data center.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Energy consumption and the environmental impacts it creates are a central issue for data centers.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Power draw ranges from a few kilowatts (kW) for small server racks to several tens of megawatts (MW) for large facilities.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Modern hyperscale data centers can exhibit power densities exceeding 100 times those of conventional office buildings, primarily due to the high concentration of servers and cooling systems required to manage continuous digital workloads.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] For higher power density facilities, electricity costs are a dominant operating expense and account for over 10% of the total cost of ownership (TCO) of a data center.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] As of 2024, data centers in the U.S. are primarily powered by natural gas, which supplies 40% of their electricity (with renewable energy at 24%, nuclear at about 20%, and coal at about 15%).
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] The *Associated Press* reported that electricity for AI data centers in the U.S. would likely come from natural gas or oil, as companies prefer using currently available power plants, which primarily use fossil fuels.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Fossil energy is also often cheaper in locations where data centers are developed, and experts believe that energy demands from generative AI and data centers would be difficult to fulfill with renewable energy alone.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Some companies such as Google, Amazon, and Meta have expressed interest in nuclear power for their data centers.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] As of 2020, according to the IEA, solar photovoltaic-generated electricity is at its lowest cost in history.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Other data centers, including xAI's Colossus, OpenAI's Stargate, and Meta's Prometheus use their own off-grid natural gas plants.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Electric vehicle and lithium-ion batteries have also been used for powering data centers, including for Colossus.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Power utility companies make upgrades to their infrastructure to handle demands of new data centers, and the price for these changes typically falls on residential or smaller commercial consumers.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] In 2025, the Mountain Valley Pipeline announced plans to expand its capacity by 25% to meet energy needs for data centers.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] In December 2025, the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC) published a unanimous order allowing data centers in the U.S. to have a direct connection with power plants.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] United States Secretary of Energy Chris Wright expressed support for un-retiring coal plants to power AI data centers.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Electricity demands from AI data centers have slowed or reversed the retirement of peaking power plants in the U.S.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] For example, in 2025, Southern Company announced that energy use from data centers would prevent the company from retiring coal-fired power plants as it had earlier promised.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] In Nevada, the Desert Research Institute (DRI) calculated that 35% of the state's energy production could go to data centers by the year 2030 if all projects planned in the state as of 2026 are completed.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] DRI also stated, in areas where there are clusters of data centers, local consumers may end up paying the extra cost of expanding infrastructure.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] In 2024, data centers were estimated to account for about 1.5% of global electricity consumption (approximately 415 TWh) and around 1% of greenhouse gas emissions according to U.S.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] However, the rapid expansion is causing projections to rise sharply.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Due to accelerated demand from AI, data center's global electricity consumption is projected to more than double to around 945 TWh by 2030 in the IEA's base-case scenario, which represents just under 3% of 2030 total global electricity consumption.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] This growing electricity demand, much of which is still generated by fossil fuels, increases the potential environmental impacts.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] In addition to operational energy demand, embodied life cycle emissions should be considered, which include the extraction, manufacturing, transportation, and recycling or disposal of materials used in the construction of facilities and hardware.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Global data center carbon dioxide emissions are projected to rise from an estimated 220 million tonnes in 2024 to 300–320 million tonnes by 2035.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] In 2024, Google and Microsoft each consumed more power than over 100 countries.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] As a result, there is increasing industry pressure for decarbonization.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Companies are pursuing direct clean energy agreements, such as Tencent who has pledged to be carbon neutral by 2030, and Microsoft's 2024 agreement to re-open the Three Mile Island nuclear power plant to provide 100% of the electric power for its AI data centers for 20 years.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] The most commonly used energy efficiency metric for data centers is power usage effectiveness (PUE), calculated as the ratio of total power entering the data center divided by the power used by IT equipment.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] PUE measures the percentage of power used by overhead devices (cooling, lighting, etc.).
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] The average U.S. data center has a PUE of 2.0, meaning two watts of total power (overhead + IT equipment) for every watt delivered to IT equipment.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] State-of-the-art data centers are estimated to have a PUE of roughly 1.2.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Google publishes quarterly efficiency metrics from its data centers in operation.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] PUEs of as low as 1.01 have been achieved with two-phase immersion cooling.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] The EPA has an Energy Star rating for standalone or large data centers.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] To qualify for the ecolabel, a data center must be within the top quartile in energy efficiency of all reported facilities.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] The Energy Efficiency Improvement Act of 2015 (U.S.) requires federal facilities—including data centers—to operate more efficiently.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] California's Title 24 (2014) of the California Code of Regulations mandates that every newly constructed data center must have some form of airflow containment in place to optimize energy efficiency.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] The European Union (EU) also has a similar initiative: EU Code of Conduct for Data Centres.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Efficiency improvements and renewable energy integration are helping offset some emissions, but fossil fuels remain a major electricity source for data center operations worldwide.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] In 2011, server racks in data centers were designed for more than 25 kW, and the typical server was estimated to waste about 30% of the electricity it consumed.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] The energy demand for information storage systems is also rising.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] A high-availability data center is estimated to have a 1 MW demand and consume $20 million in electricity over its lifetime, with cooling representing 35% to 45% of the data center's total cost of ownership.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Calculations show that in two years, the cost of powering and cooling a server could be equal to the cost of purchasing the server hardware.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Research in 2018 showed that a substantial amount of energy could still be conserved by optimizing IT refresh rates and increasing server use.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Research for optimizing task scheduling is also underway, with researchers looking to implement energy-efficient scheduling algorithms that could reduce energy consumption by anywhere between 6% and 44%.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] In 2011, Facebook, Rackspace, and others founded the Open Compute Project (OCP) to develop and publish open standards for greener data center computing technologies.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] As part of the project, Facebook published the designs of its server, which it had built for its first dedicated data center in Prineville.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Making servers taller left space for more effective heat sinks and enabled the use of fans that moved more air with less energy.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] By not buying commercial off-the-shelf servers, energy consumption due to unnecessary expansion slots on the motherboard and unneeded components, such as a graphics card, was also saved.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] In 2016, Google joined the project and published the designs of its 48V DC shallow data center rack.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] This design had long been part of Google data centers.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] By eliminating the multiple transformers usually deployed in data centers, Google had achieved a 30% increase in energy efficiency.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] In 2017, sales for data center hardware built to OCP designs topped $1.2 billion and are expected to reach $6 billion by 2021.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Power is the largest recurring cost to the user of a data center.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] In 2008, the ASHRAE recommended a temperature range of 64.4 °F (18.0 °C) to 80.6 °F (27.0 °C), though some data centers could operate at higher temperatures.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] However, cooling at or below 70 °F (21 °C) wastes money and energy.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Furthermore, overcooling equipment in environments with a high relative humidity can expose equipment to a high amount of moisture that facilitates the growth of salt deposits on conductive filaments in the circuitry.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] A **power and cooling analysis**, also referred to as a thermal assessment, measures the relative temperatures in specific areas as well as the capacity of the cooling systems to handle specific ambient temperatures.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Power cooling density is a measure of how much square footage the center can cool at maximum capacity.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] The cooling of data centers is the second largest power consumer after servers, with cooling taking about 7% to 30% of energy usage (depending on efficiency), compared to an average of 60% of energy used by servers.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] An energy efficiency analysis measures the energy use of data center IT and facilities equipment.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] A typical energy efficiency analysis measures factors such as a data center's Power Use Effectiveness (PUE) against industry standards, identifies mechanical and electrical sources of inefficiency, and identifies air-management metrics.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] However, the limitation of most current metrics and approaches is they do not include IT in the analysis.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Case studies have shown that by addressing energy efficiency holistically in a data center, major efficiencies can be achieved that are not possible otherwise.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Thermal zone mapping uses sensors and computer modeling to create a three-dimensional image of the hot and cool zones in a data center.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] This information can help identify optimal positioning of data center equipment.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] For example, critical servers might be placed in a cool zone that is serviced by redundant AC units.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Data centers use a lot of power, consumed via two main usages: the power required to run the equipment and the power required to cool the equipment.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Power efficiency reduces the first category.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Cooling cost reduction through natural means includes location decisions.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] When the focus is avoiding good fiber connectivity, power grid connections, and people concentrations to manage the equipment, a data center can be miles away from users.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Mass data centers like Google or Facebook do not need to be near population centers.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Arctic locations that can use outside air, which provides cooling, are becoming more popular.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Countries with favorable conditions, such as Canada, Finland, Sweden, Norway, and Switzerland are trying to attract cloud computing data centers.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Singapore lifted a three-year ban on new data centers in April 2022.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] A major data center hub for the Asia-Pacific region, Singapore lifted its moratorium on new data center projects in 2022, granting four new projects, but rejecting more than 16 data center applications from over 20 received.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] It is very difficult to reuse the heat that comes from air-cooled data centers.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] For this reason, data center infrastructures are more often equipped with heat pumps.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] The rapid growth of artificial intelligence (AI) and high-performance computing workloads has increased attention on data center power infrastructure, particularly the relationship between electrical reliability, deployment timelines, energy costs, and decarbonization objectives.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Industry publications have described phased approaches to infrastructure development that enable operators to deploy power capacity rapidly while maintaining pathways toward lower-carbon energy systems as technologies, fuel availability, grid capacity, and economics evolve.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Recent industry discussion has also emphasized "speed-to-power" as a significant consideration in data center development, reflecting the growing importance of securing electrical capacity and resilient power systems within increasingly compressed project timelines.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] In the 2020s, the rapid growth of data center construction gave rise to policy debates over tax incentives, electricity grid, water resources, and climate commitments.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] By 2024, at least 36 U.S. states had introduced specific tax incentives aimed at attracting data center investment, most often in the form of sales tax exemptions on servers, networking equipment, and electricity.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Virginia hosts the largest concentration of data centers in the U.S., and a December 2024 audit by its Joint Legislative Audit and Review Commission (JLARC) put the industry's annual contribution at roughly 74,000 jobs and $9.1 billion in gross state product.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] The audit reported that the state's sales and use tax exemption was claimed by about 90% of operators and that reduced state revenue by an estimated $928 million in fiscal year 2023.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Thus, JLARC concluded that ending the exemption would likely shrink Virginia's share of new data center investment.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Economists have debated the effectiveness of such incentives more broadly.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Further, research by Timothy Bartik of the Upjohn Institute estimated that economic development incentives change firm location decisions in only 2% to 25% of cases.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] In response to tax exemption policies, several jurisdictions have started to reevaluate incentives for data centers.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] In 2024, the Georgia General Assembly passed legislation to terminate the state's data center sales tax exemption.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] However, the bill was ultimately vetoed by Governor Brian Kemp.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] In another case in 2026, the Virginia Senate voted 28 to 12 to phase out the state's data center sales tax exemption as part of broader budget negotiations.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Most large data centers use water for evaporative cooling of their servers, and the volumes involved have drawn growing scrutiny.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] A 2021 study in *npj Clean Water* estimated that U.S. data centers directly consume about 1.7 billion liters of water per day, with up to 57% of that drawn from potable supplies, and noted that fewer than one-third of operators measured their water use at the time.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] A separate study published in *Environmental Research Letters* found that about one-fifth of direct water use by U.S. data centers came from moderately or highly water-stressed watersheds, and that nearly half of the country's servers ran on electricity drawn from water-stressed regions.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] According to a 2024 Berkeley Lab report, data centers in the U.S. had used approximately 17 billion gallons of water.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] The same report expected hyperscale data centers specifically to use 16 to 33 billion gallons of water per year by 2028.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] In Virginia, the December 2024 JLARC audit reported that data centers in the state consumed about 2.1 billion gallons of water in 2023, an 86% increase since 2019, and that roughly one-third of that came from reclaimed water rather than potable supplies.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] The audit recommended that local governments be authorized to require water-use estimates as part of the data center permitting process.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] There is no federal U.S. standard requiring data center operators to disclose water consumption, and access to facility-level data has often been limited by non-disclosure agreements (NDAs) with host municipalities.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] In 2022, the city of The Dalles, Oregon, settled a public records lawsuit brought by *The Oregonian*, after which Google ended its nationwide practice of treating site-level water use as a trade secret.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] In 2025, several states considered legislation to require data centers to disclose water use, including bills in Virginia, California, and New Jersey, although each was vetoed by the state's governor that year.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] The growth of data center electricity demand in the 2020s has prompted regulatory debates over grid capacity, transmission planning, and how the costs of new infrastructure should be allocated among customers.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] The 2024 Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory (LBNL) report on U.S. data center energy use, prepared at the request of the U.S.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Congress, estimated that data centers accounted for about 4.4% of national electricity consumption in 2023 and projected a rise to between 6.7% and 12% by 2028, depending on growth scenarios.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] In 2025, the IEA projected that data centers would account for nearly half of new U.S. electricity demand growth through 2030.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] The North American Electric Reliability Corporation (NERC), the federally designated electric reliability organization for the U.S., identified data centers as the single largest driver of projected demand growth in its 2024 long-term reliability assessment.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Additionally, NERC documented a voltage event in the PJM Interconnection region in July 2024, in which roughly 1,500 megawatts of data center load disconnected simultaneously across about 60 facilities.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] How the costs of meeting this demand are shared has also become a central policy question.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] The JLARC audit in 2024 estimated that, without any changes to how rates are designed, typical residential customers of Dominion Energy Virginia could see their bills rise by $14 to $37 per month by 2040 because of data center-driven grid investment.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] As such, the report recommended creating a separate customer rate class for large data centers.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Some researchers have urged caution in interpreting demand projections.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Furthermore, a 2024 commentary in the journal *Joule* argued that public estimates of future data center electricity use vary widely and that utilities have historically over-forecasted load growth, and called for more transparent data on actual facility-level consumption.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] The growth of data centers has raised questions about whether the renewable energy commitments made by their operators are consistent with broader climate goals.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Many large operators report meeting electricity-related emissions targets through annual purchases of renewable energy certificates (RECs) or matching their total annual consumption with renewable generation.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] In 2022, a study by *Nature Climate Change* analyzed 115 companies with Science Based Targets.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] It found that about 42% of their reported Scope 2 emissions reductions disappeared once REC-based claims were excluded.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] This directly suggests that some corporate climate progress reflected accounting choices rather than actual reductions in grid emissions.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] In response, some operators and researchers have proposed 24/7 carbon-free energy matching.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Under this approach, every hour of a facility's electricity use must be matched with carbon-free generation on the same regional grid.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] The authors found that annual or volumetric matching did little to cut grid emissions under current U.S. policy.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Hourly 24/7 matching cut more, but it cost about $13 to $30 more per megawatt-hour.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] The tension between data center expansion and corporate climate goals has also become apparent in the operators' own disclosures of information.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] In 2024, Google reported its greenhouse gas emissions had risen by about 48% since 2019, attributing the increase in large part to data center electricity use associated with AI workloads.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Similarly, Microsoft reported in 2024 that its emissions had risen by about 29% since 2020, citing the construction and operation of new data centers.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p01] Moreover, the IEA projected in 2025 that global data center carbon dioxide emissions could peak at around 320 million tonnes by 2030 before declining slightly through 2035, with the trajectory depending heavily on the carbon intensity of the electricity supplied to new facilities.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p02] Data centers have significant impacts on local ecologies, politics, and utility infrastructure.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p02] Political and economic incentives such as tax breaks, land deals, or government subsidies drive data center growth in areas where these incentives are available.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p02] Data centers are frequently located in rural areas, where they may displace agriculture.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p02] Growth in the data center industry has prompted several debates about environmental impacts, especially the massive energy and water demands.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p02] The supply chains, emissions, and e-waste also impose significant planetary impacts, raising questions of environmental injustice toward marginalized communities that frequently bear these burdens.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p02] Multiple studies and experts have found that data centers do not bring high-paying jobs to local communities in proportion to the tax subsidies they receive.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p02] The rapid expansion of AI data centers has raised significant concerns over their water consumption, particularly in drought-prone regions.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p02] According to the IEA, a single 100-megawatt data center, using 2400 MWh of electricity per day, can use up to 2,000,000 litres (530,000 US gal) of water per day.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p02] The electricity use is equivalent to that of 60,000–120,000 households in the U.S., while water use is equivalent about 6,500 households.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p02] Water usage can be divided into three categories: on-site (direct usage from data centers), off-site (indirect usage from electricity), and supply-chain (water usage from manufacturing processes).
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p02] On-site water use refers to the direct water consumed by the data center for the cooling of its equipment.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p02] Water is used specifically for space humidification (adding moisture to the air), evaporative cooling systems (cooling air before entering server rooms), and cooling towers (removing heat from the facility).
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p02] Off-site water use is the indirect water usage from the electricity generated in data centers.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p02] It is estimated that 56% of U.S. data centers' electricity comes from fossil fuels in thermal power stations, which use water to generate power via steam.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p02] Lastly, data centers consume water through the process of AI chip and server manufacturing.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p02] These chips, specifically, consume a vast amount of ultrapure water for fabrication and cooling of semiconductor plants.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p02] While this scope of water usage is not as significant as on-site and off-site water usage, it is still a contributing factor.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p02] Globally, since 2022, more than two-thirds of new data centers have been built in water-stressed areas, including Texas, Arizona, Saudi Arabia, and India, where freshwater scarcity is already a critical issue.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p02] The global water footprint of data centers is estimated at 560 billion litres (150×10^9 US gal) annually, a figure projected to double by 2030 due to increasing AI demand.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p02] In regions like Aragon, Spain, Amazon's planned data centers are licensed to withdraw 755,720 cubic metres (612.67 acre⋅ft) of water per year, sparking conflicts with farmers who rely on the same dwindling supplies.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p02] Similar tensions have arisen in Chile, the Netherlands, and Uruguay, where communities protest the diversion of water for tech infrastructure.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p02] Tech companies, including Microsoft, Google, and Amazon, have pledged to become "water positive" by 2030, aiming to replenish more water than they consume.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p02] However, critics argue that such commitments often rely on water offsetting, which does not address acute local shortages.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p02] At least 59 additional data centers are planned for water-stressed U.S. regions by 2028, and AI's global water demand is projected to reach 6.6 billion cubic metres (1,700×10^9 US gal) by 2027.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p02] Data centers generate significant electronic waste (e-waste) due to the frequent replacement of hardware such as servers, GPUs, CPUs, memory, and storage devices, often every 2–5 years to meet demands for digital transformation and AI.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p02] Globally, e-waste totaled 62 million metric tons in 2022, with generative AI projected to contribute 1.2 to 5 million metric tons annually by 2030, including valuable metals like copper and gold, and hazardous substances such as lead and mercury.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p02] In the U.S., data centers contribute to an annual loss of $10 billion in discarded e-waste value, including $4 billion in precious metals.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p02] Only 22% of global e-waste is formally collected and recycled, exacerbating environmental pollution and health risks in informal processing sites, often in developing countries where exported waste is handled.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p02] From a political ecology perspective, data center e-waste highlights power imbalances in resource management and environmental justice, as tech corporations benefit from tax incentives while externalizing costs to marginalized communities through toxic exports and landfill burdens.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p02] This ties into debates on the commons, where shared resources like metals are depleted without equitable governance.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p02] Mitigation strategies include modular hardware designs, secure data erasure for reuse, and extended producer responsibility policies to reduce waste by up to 86% in optimized scenarios.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p02] According to one 2025 energy model, the U.S. could see energy prices increase 8% nationally by 2030.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p02] Higher electricity prices are already occurring in some regions, particularly those with lots of data centers like Santa Clara, California, and parts of upstate New York.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p02] Data centers have also generated concerns in Northern Virginia about whether residents will have to foot the bill for future power lines.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p02] It has also made it harder to develop housing in London.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p02] A Bank of America Institute report in July 2024 found that increased demand for electricity due in part to AI has been pushing electricity prices higher and is a significant contributor to electricity inflation.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p02] A Harvard Law School report in March 2025 found that because utilities are increasingly in competition to attract data center contracts from big tech companies, they are likely hiding subsidies to those trillion-dollar companies in power prices by raising costs for American consumers.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p02] Data centers have increasingly been analyzed through the lens of political ecology, which explores the intersections of power, politics, and environmental change in technological infrastructure.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p02] Scholars argue that these facilities reshape urban and rural landscapes by existing in marginalized or post-industrial areas, often repurposing abandoned sites while promising economic revitalization through job creation and tax revenues.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p02] For instance, hyperscale data centers in rural towns like Prineville, Oregon, or Luleå, Sweden, challenge traditional core-periphery dynamics but can exacerbate global inequalities in digital access and resource distribution.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p02] In the context of digital transformation, data centers enable the expansion of cloud computing, AI, and machine learning, but at significant ecological and social costs.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p02] Critics from science and technology studies (STS) highlight how corporate sustainability pledges, such as carbon neutrality targets by companies like Microsoft and Google, often rely on offsets and renewable subsidies that privatize benefits while causing social and environmental harms.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p02] This ties into debates on the commons, where data centers' intensive use of public resources (like electricity grids and water supplies) represents an enclosure, with tech firms receiving tax breaks and priority access at the expense of local communities.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p02] Jobs created by data centers tend to be temporary or few in number.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p02] A study found the productivity increases enabled by data centers are multiple times larger than gross external damages.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p02] Social mobilizations against data centers help shape the discourse around growth of the industry, raise public awareness of issues data centers present, and may impact public policy.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p02] Groups opposed to new data center projects have expressed concern that digital infrastructure exploits local resources 'to the benefit of actors and institutions residing elsewhere'.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p02] This may occur when data being processed in a facility belongs to actors in other countries, but local people bear the burdens of water and energy use.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p02] In the U.S., bipartisan community resistance to data center development has grown, with residents voicing concerns about water scarcity, rising utility bills, noise pollution, and urban sprawl.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p02] Facilities in rural areas of the U.S. have been focal points for local resistance.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p02] Data Center Watch reported that multiple projects collectively worth $64 billion had been stopped or delayed between May 2024 and March 2025.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p02] An additional $98 billion worth of projects were blocked or delayed between March and June 2025.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p02] A Gallup poll taken in March 2026 reported seven out of ten Americans oppose data center projects in their area.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p02] Outside of the U.S., protests in the Netherlands led to a temporary national ban on new mega-centers in 2022.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p02] In Chile, protests by activists to protect water reserves led to Google withdrawing plans to build a data center.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p02] In the United Kingdom, "March Against the Machines" protests were held.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p02] Residents have been concerned about air, water, and noise pollution, as well as property devaluation, traffic, and the risk of fires.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p02] Other environmental concerns involving AI data centers include e-waste and the embodied energy of construction materials, such as concrete and cement.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p02] data center, they would orbit above the dawn / dusk transition of the planet.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p02] Housing data centers in space has been proposed for low Earth orbit (LEO).
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p02] The theoretical advantages are that of space-based solar power, in addition to aiding in weather forecasting and weather prediction computation from weather satellites, and the ability to freely scale up.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p02] However, it is difficult to design cooling systems in space, as convection is not available and sunlight causes large temperature fluctuations.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p02] Other challenges include damage from cosmic rays and micrometeorites.
[src:datacenter-fabric/data-center-p02] The design and shape of data centers could change rapidly in the not-too-distant future with the advent of new technologies, such as quantum computing, biocomputation, and synthetic DNA data storage, as examples.
[src:datacenter-fabric/fat-tree] The **fat tree network** is a universal network for provably efficient communication.
[src:datacenter-fabric/fat-tree] Leiserson of the MIT in 1985. k-ary n-trees, the type of fat-trees commonly used in most high-performance networks, were initially formalized in 1997.
[src:datacenter-fabric/fat-tree] In a tree data structure, every branch has the same thickness (bandwidth), regardless of their place in the hierarchy—they are all "skinny" (*skinny* in this context means low-bandwidth).
[src:datacenter-fabric/fat-tree] In a fat tree, branches nearer the top of the hierarchy are "fatter" (thicker) than branches further down the hierarchy.
[src:datacenter-fabric/fat-tree] In a telecommunications network, the branches are data links; the varied thickness (bandwidth) of the data links allows for more efficient and technology-specific use.
[src:datacenter-fabric/fat-tree] Mesh and hypercube topologies have communication requirements that follow a rigid algorithm, and cannot be tailored to specific packaging technologies.
[src:datacenter-fabric/fat-tree] Supercomputers that use a fat tree network include the two fastest as of late 2018, Summit and Sierra, as well as Tianhe-2, the Meiko Scientific CS-2, Yellowstone, the Earth Simulator, the Cray X2, the Connection Machine CM-5, and various Altix supercomputers.
[src:datacenter-fabric/fat-tree] Mercury Computer Systems applied a variant of the fat tree topology—the hypertree network—to their multicomputers.
[src:datacenter-fabric/fat-tree] In this architecture, 2 to 360 compute nodes are arranged in a circuit-switched fat tree network.
[src:datacenter-fabric/fat-tree] Each node has local memory that can be mapped by any other node.
[src:datacenter-fabric/fat-tree] Each node in this heterogeneous system could be an Intel i860, a PowerPC, or a group of three SHARC digital signal processors.
[src:datacenter-fabric/fat-tree] The fat tree network was particularly well suited to fast Fourier transform computations, which customers used for such signal processing tasks as radar, sonar, and medical imaging.
[src:datacenter-fabric/fat-tree] In August 2008, a team of computer scientists at UCSD published a scalable design for network architecture that uses a topology inspired by the fat tree topology to realize networks that scale better than those of previous hierarchical networks.
[src:datacenter-fabric/fat-tree] The architecture uses commodity switches that are cheaper and more power-efficient than high-end modular data center switches.
[src:datacenter-fabric/fat-tree] This topology is actually a special instance of a Clos network, rather than a fat-tree as described above.
[src:datacenter-fabric/fat-tree] That is because the edges near the root are emulated by many links to separate parents instead of a single high-capacity link to a single parent.
[src:datacenter-fabric/fat-tree] However, many authors continue to use the term in this way.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-architecture] In telecommunications, the specification of a network architecture may also include a detailed description of products and services delivered via a communications network, as well as detailed rate and billing structures under which services are compensated.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-architecture] The network architecture of the Internet is predominantly expressed by its use of the Internet protocol suite, rather than a specific model for interconnecting networks or nodes in the network, or the usage of specific types of hardware links.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-architecture] The Open Systems Interconnection model (OSI model) defines and codifies the concept of layered network architecture.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-architecture] Abstraction layers are used to subdivide a communications system further into smaller manageable parts.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-architecture] A layer is a collection of similar functions that provide services to the layer above it and receives services from the layer below it.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-architecture] On each layer, an instance provides services to the instances at the layer above and requests services from the layer below.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-architecture] In distributed computing, the *network architecture* often describes the structure and classification of a distributed application architecture, as the participating nodes in a distributed application are often referred to as a *network*.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-architecture] For example, the applications architecture of the public switched telephone network (PSTN) has been termed the Intelligent Network.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-architecture] There are a number of specific classifications but all lie on a continuum between the dumb network (e.g. the Internet) and the intelligent network (e.g. the PSTN).
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-architecture] A popular example of such usage of the term in distributed applications, as well as permanent virtual circuits, is the organization of nodes in peer-to-peer (P2P) services and networks.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-architecture] P2P networks usually implement overlay networks running over an underlying physical or logical network.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-architecture] These overlay networks may implement certain organizational structures of the nodes according to several distinct models, the network architecture of the system.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] Network topology is the topological structure of a network and may be depicted physically or logically.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] It is an application of graph theory wherein communicating devices are modeled as nodes and the connections between the devices are modeled as links or lines between the nodes.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] **Physical topology** is the placement of the various components of a network (e.g., device location and cable installation), while **logical topology** illustrates how data flows within a network.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] Distances between nodes, physical interconnections, transmission rates, or signal types may differ between two different networks, yet their logical topologies may be identical.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] A network's physical topology is a particular concern of the physical layer of the OSI model.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] Examples of network topologies are found in local area networks (LAN), a common computer network installation.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] Any given node in the LAN has one or more physical links to other devices in the network; graphically mapping these links results in a geometric shape that can be used to describe the physical topology of the network.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] A wide variety of physical topologies have been used in LANs, including ring, bus, mesh and star.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] Conversely, mapping the data flow between the components determines the logical topology of the network.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] In comparison, Controller Area Networks, common in vehicles, are primarily distributed control system networks of one or more controllers interconnected with sensors and actuators over, invariably, a physical bus topology.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] Two basic categories of network topologies exist: physical topologies and logical topologies.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] The transmission medium layout used to link devices is the physical topology of the network.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] For conductive or fiber optical mediums, this refers to the layout of cabling, the locations of nodes, and the links between the nodes and the cabling.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] The physical topology of a network is determined by the capabilities of the network access devices and media, the level of control or fault tolerance desired, and the cost associated with cabling or telecommunication circuits.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] In contrast, logical topology is the way that the signals act on the network media, or the way that the data passes through the network from one device to the next without regard to the physical interconnection of the devices.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] A network's logical topology is not necessarily the same as its physical topology.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] For example, the original twisted pair Ethernet using repeater hubs was a logical bus topology carried on a physical star topology.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] Token Ring is a logical ring topology, but is wired as a physical star from the media access unit.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] Logical topologies are often closely associated with media access control methods and protocols.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] Some networks are able to dynamically change their logical topology through configuration changes to their routers and switches.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] The transmission media (often referred to in the literature as the *physical media*) used to link devices to form a computer network include electrical cables (Ethernet, HomePNA, power line communication, G.hn), optical fiber (fiber-optic communication), and radio waves (wireless networking).
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] In the OSI model, these are defined at layers 1 and 2 — the physical layer and the data link layer.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] A widely adopted *family* of transmission media used in local area network (LAN) technology is collectively known as Ethernet.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] The media and protocol standards that enable communication between networked devices over Ethernet are defined by IEEE 802.3.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] Ethernet transmits data over both copper and fiber cables.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] Wireless LAN standards (e.g., those defined by IEEE 802.11) use radio waves, or others use infrared signals as a transmission medium.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] Power line communication uses a building's power cabling to transmit data.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] The orders of the following wired technologies are, roughly, from slowest to fastest transmission speed.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] Price is a main factor distinguishing wired and wireless technology options in a business.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] Wireless options command a price premium that can make purchasing wired computers, printers and other devices a financial benefit.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] Before making the decision to purchase hard-wired technology products, a review of the restrictions and limitations of the selections is necessary.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] Business and employee needs may override any cost considerations.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] Both cases have a large round-trip delay time, which gives slow two-way communication, but does not prevent sending large amounts of information.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] Network nodes are the points of connection of the transmission medium to transmitters and receivers of the electrical, optical, or radio signals carried in the medium.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] Nodes may be associated with a computer, but certain types may have only a microcontroller at a node or possibly no programmable device at all.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] In the simplest of serial arrangements, one RS-232 transmitter can be connected by a pair of wires to one receiver, forming two nodes on one link, or a point-to-point topology.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] Some protocols permit a single node to only either transmit or receive (e.g., ARINC 429).
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] Other protocols have nodes that can both transmit and receive into a single channel (e.g., CAN can have many transceivers connected to a single bus).
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] A network interface controller (NIC) is computer hardware that provides a computer with the ability to access the transmission media, and has the ability to process low-level network information.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] For example, the NIC may have a connector for accepting a cable, or an aerial for wireless transmission and reception, and the associated circuitry.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] The NIC responds to traffic addressed to a network address for either the NIC or the computer as a whole.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] In Ethernet networks, each network interface controller has a unique Media Access Control (MAC) address—usually stored in the controller's permanent memory.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] To avoid address conflicts between network devices, the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE) maintains and administers MAC address uniqueness.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] The size of an Ethernet MAC address is six octets.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] The three most significant octets are reserved to identify NIC manufacturers.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] These manufacturers, using only their assigned prefixes, uniquely assign the three least-significant octets of every Ethernet interface they produce.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] A repeater is an electronic device that receives a network signal, cleans it of unnecessary noise and regenerates it.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] The signal may be reformed or retransmitted at a higher power level, to the other side of an obstruction, possibly using a different transmission medium, so that the signal can cover longer distances without degradation.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] Commercial repeaters have extended RS-232 segments from 15 meters to over a kilometer.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] In most twisted pair Ethernet configurations, repeaters are required for cable that runs longer than 100 meters.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] With fiber optics, repeaters can be tens or even hundreds of kilometers apart.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] Repeaters work within the physical layer of the OSI model; that is, there is no end-to-end change in the physical protocol across the repeater, or repeater pair, even if a different physical layer may be used between the ends of the repeater, or repeater pair.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] Repeaters require a small amount of time to regenerate the signal.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] This can cause a propagation delay that affects network performance and may affect proper function.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] As a result, many network architectures limit the number of repeaters that can be used in a row, e.g., the Ethernet 5-4-3 rule.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] A repeater with multiple ports is known as hub, an Ethernet hub in Ethernet networks, a USB hub in USB networks.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] A network bridge connects and filters traffic between two network segments at the data link layer (layer 2) of the OSI model to form a single network.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] This breaks the network's collision domain but maintains a unified broadcast domain.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] Network segmentation breaks down a large, congested network into an aggregation of smaller, more efficient networks.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] A network switch is a device that forwards and filters OSI layer 2 datagrams (frames) between ports based on the destination MAC address in each frame.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] A switch is distinct from a hub in that it only forwards the frames to the physical ports involved in the communication, rather than all ports connected.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] It can be thought of as a multi-port bridge.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] It learns to associate physical ports to MAC addresses by examining the source addresses of received frames.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] If an unknown destination is targeted, the switch broadcasts to all ports but the source.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] Switches normally have numerous ports, facilitating a star topology for devices and cascading additional switches.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] Multi-layer switches are capable of routing based on layer 3 addressing or additional logical levels.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] The term *switch* is often used loosely to include devices such as routers and bridges, as well as devices that may distribute traffic based on load or based on application content (e.g., a Web URL identifier).
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] A router is an internetworking device that forwards packets between networks by processing the routing information included in the packet or datagram (Internet protocol information from layer 3).
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] The routing information is often processed in conjunction with the routing table (or forwarding table).
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] A router uses its routing table to determine where to forward packets.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] A destination in a routing table can include a black hole because data can go into it; however, no further processing is done for said data, i.e., the packets are dropped.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] Modems (MOdulator-DEModulator) are used to connect network nodes via wire not originally designed for digital network traffic, or for wireless.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] To do this, one or more carrier signals are modulated by the digital signal to produce an analog signal that can be tailored to give the required properties for transmission.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] Modems are commonly used for telephone lines, using a digital subscriber line technology.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] A firewall is a network device for controlling network security and access rules.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] Firewalls are typically configured to reject access requests from unrecognized sources while allowing actions from recognized ones.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] The vital role firewalls play in network security grows in parallel with the constant increase in cyber attacks.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] The study of network topology recognizes eight basic topologies: point-to-point, bus, star, ring or circular, mesh, tree, hybrid, or daisy chain.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] The simplest topology with a dedicated link between two endpoints.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] Easiest to understand of the variations of point-to-point topology is a point-to-point communication channel that appears, to the user, to be permanently associated with the two endpoints.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] A child's tin can telephone is one example of a *physical dedicated* channel.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] Using circuit-switching or packet-switching technologies, a point-to-point circuit can be set up dynamically and dropped when no longer needed.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] Switched point-to-point topologies are the basic model of conventional telephony.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] The value of a permanent point-to-point network is unimpeded communications between the two endpoints.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] The value of an on-demand point-to-point connection is proportional to the number of potential pairs of subscribers and has been expressed as Metcalfe's Law.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] Daisy chaining is accomplished by connecting each computer in series to the next.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] If a message is intended for a computer partway down the line, each system bounces it along in sequence until it reaches the destination.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] A daisy-chained network can take two basic forms: linear and ring.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] In local area networks using bus topology, each node is connected by interface connectors to a single central cable.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] This is the 'bus', also referred to as the backbone, or trunk – all data transmission between nodes in the network is transmitted over this common transmission medium and is able to be received by all nodes in the network simultaneously.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] A signal containing the address of the intended receiving machine travels from a source machine in both directions to all machines connected to the bus until it finds the intended recipient, which then accepts the data.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] If the machine address does not match the intended address for the data, the data portion of the signal is ignored.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] Since the bus topology consists of only one wire, it is less expensive to implement than other topologies, but the savings are offset by the higher cost of managing the network.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] Additionally, since the network is dependent on the single cable, it can be the single point of failure of the network.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] In this topology, data being transferred may be accessed by any node.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] In a linear bus network, all of the nodes of the network are connected to a common transmission medium, which has just two endpoints.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] When the electrical signal reaches the end of the bus, the signal is reflected back down the line, causing unwanted interference.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] To prevent this, the two endpoints of the bus are normally terminated with a device called a terminator.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] In star topology (also called hub-and-spoke), every peripheral node (computer workstation or any other peripheral) is connected to a central node called a hub or switch.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] The hub is the server and the peripherals are the clients.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] The network does not necessarily have to resemble a star to be classified as a star network, but all of the peripheral nodes on the network must be connected to one central hub.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] All traffic that traverses the network passes through the central hub, which acts as a signal repeater.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] The star topology is considered the easiest topology to design and implement.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] One advantage of the star topology is the simplicity of adding additional nodes.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] The primary disadvantage of the star topology is that the hub represents a single point of failure.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] Also, since all peripheral communication must flow through the central hub, the aggregate central bandwidth forms a network bottleneck for large clusters.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] The extended star network topology extends a physical star topology by one or more repeaters between the central node and the peripheral (or 'spoke') nodes.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] The repeaters are used to extend the maximum transmission distance of the physical layer, the point-to-point distance between the central node and the peripheral nodes.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] Repeaters allow greater transmission distance, further than would be possible using just the transmitting power of the central node.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] The use of repeaters can also overcome limitations from the standard upon which the physical layer is based.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] A physical extended star topology in which repeaters are replaced with hubs or switches is a type of hybrid network topology and is referred to as a physical hierarchical star topology, although some texts make no distinction between the two topologies.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] A physical hierarchical star topology can also be referred as a tier-star topology.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] This topology differs from a tree topology in the way star networks are connected together.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] A tier-star topology uses a central node, while a tree topology uses a central bus and can also be referred to as a star-bus network.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] A ring topology is a daisy chain in a closed loop.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] Data travels around the ring in one direction.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] When one node sends data to another, the data passes through each intermediate node on the ring until it reaches its destination.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] The intermediate nodes repeat (retransmit) the data to keep the signal strong.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] Every node is a peer; there is no hierarchical relationship of clients and servers.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] If one node is unable to retransmit data, it severs communication between the nodes before and after it in the bus.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] The value of fully meshed networks is proportional to the exponent of the number of subscribers, assuming that communicating groups of any two endpoints, up to and including all the endpoints, is approximated by Reed's Law.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] In a *fully connected network*, all nodes are interconnected.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] (In graph theory this is called a complete graph.) The simplest fully connected network is a two-node network.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] A fully connected network doesn't need to use packet switching or broadcasting.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] This makes it impractical for large networks.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] This kind of topology does not trip and affect other nodes in the network.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] In a partially connected network, certain nodes are connected to exactly one other node, but some nodes are connected to two or more other nodes with a point-to-point link.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] This makes it possible to make use of some of the redundancy of mesh topology that is physically fully connected, without the expense and complexity required for a connection between every node in the network.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] Hybrid topology is also known as hybrid network.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] Hybrid networks combine two or more topologies in such a way that the resulting network does not exhibit one of the standard topologies (e.g., bus, star, ring, etc.).
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] For example, a tree network (or *star-bus network*) is a hybrid topology in which star networks are interconnected via bus networks.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] However, a tree network connected to another tree network is still topologically a tree network, not a distinct network type.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] A hybrid topology is always produced when two different basic network topologies are connected.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] A *star-ring* network consists of two or more ring networks connected using a multistation access unit (MAU) as a centralized hub.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] Two other hybrid network types are *hybrid mesh* and *hierarchical star*.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] The **star topology** reduces the probability of a network failure by connecting all of the peripheral nodes (computers, etc.) to a central node.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] When the physical star topology is applied to a logical bus network such as Ethernet, this central node (traditionally a hub) rebroadcasts all transmissions received from any peripheral node to all peripheral nodes on the network, sometimes including the originating node.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] All peripheral nodes may thus communicate with all others by transmitting to, and receiving from, the central node only.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] The failure of a transmission line linking any peripheral node to the central node will result in the isolation of that peripheral node from all others, but the remaining peripheral nodes will be unaffected.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] However, the disadvantage is that the failure of the central node will cause the failure of all of the peripheral nodes.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] If the central node is *passive*, the originating node must be able to tolerate the reception of an echo of its own transmission, delayed by the two-way round trip transmission time (i.e. to and from the central node) plus any delay generated in the central node.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] An *active* star network has an active central node that usually has the means to prevent echo-related problems.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] **hierarchical topology**) can be viewed as a collection of star networks arranged in a hierarchy.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] This tree structure has individual peripheral nodes (e.g., leaves) which are required to transmit to and receive from one other node only and are not required to act as repeaters or regenerators.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] Unlike the star network, the functionality of the central node may be distributed.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] As in the conventional star network, individual nodes may thus still be isolated from the network by a single-point failure of a transmission path to the node.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] If a link connecting a leaf fails, that leaf is isolated; if a connection to a non-leaf node fails, an entire section of the network becomes isolated from the rest.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] To alleviate the amount of network traffic that comes from broadcasting all signals to all nodes, more advanced central nodes were developed that are able to keep track of the identities of the nodes that are connected to the network.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] These network switches will *learn* the layout of the network by *listening* on each port during normal data transmission, examining the data packets and recording the address/identifier of each connected node and which port it is connected to in a lookup table held in memory.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] This lookup table then allows future transmissions to be forwarded to the intended destination only.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] Daisy chain topology is a way of connecting network nodes in a linear or ring structure.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] It is used to transmit messages from one node to the next until they reach the destination node.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] A daisy chain network can have two types: linear and ring.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] A linear daisy chain network is like an electrical series, where the first and last nodes are not connected.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] A ring daisy chain network is where the first and last nodes are connected, forming a loop.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] In a partially connected mesh topology, there are at least two nodes with two or more paths between them to provide redundant paths in case the link providing one of the paths fails.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] Decentralization is often used to compensate for the single-point-failure disadvantage that is present when using a single device as a central node (e.g., in star and tree networks).
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] A special kind of mesh, limiting the number of hops between two nodes, is a hypercube.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] The number of arbitrary forks in mesh networks makes them more difficult to design and implement, but their decentralized nature makes them very useful.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] This is similar in some ways to a grid network, where a linear or ring topology is used to connect systems in multiple directions.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] A multidimensional ring has a toroidal topology, for instance.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] A *fully connected network*, *complete topology*, or *full mesh topology* is a network topology in which there is a direct link between all pairs of nodes.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] In a fully connected network with n nodes, there are ${\frac {n(n-1)}{2}}\,$ direct links.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] Networks designed with this topology are usually very expensive to set up, but provide a high degree of reliability due to the multiple paths for data that are provided by the large number of redundant links between nodes.
[src:datacenter-fabric/network-topology] This topology is mostly seen in military applications.
[src:datacenter-fabric/three-tier-architecture] In software engineering, **multitier architecture** (often referred to as ***n*-tier architecture** or **layered architecture**) is a client–server architecture in which various levels of software architecture are physically separated.
[src:datacenter-fabric/three-tier-architecture] The most common use of multitier architecture is the **three-tier architecture**, which separates presentation, application processing and data management functions, such as in the case of Cisco's hierarchical internetworking model.
[src:datacenter-fabric/three-tier-architecture] Other tiers of separation may include the service layer, business layer, data access layer, and persistence layer.
[src:datacenter-fabric/three-tier-architecture] In a strict layered system, each layer depends on the layer below it and can exist without the layers above it.
[src:datacenter-fabric/three-tier-architecture] In a relaxed layered system, a layer can also depend on *all* of the layers below it, creating additional couplings between layers.
[src:datacenter-fabric/three-tier-architecture] Some multitier architectures use a hybrid approach so that some layers are strict while other layers are relaxed.
[src:datacenter-fabric/three-tier-architecture] *N*-tier architecture may also be implemented with the model–view–presenter pattern.
[src:datacenter-fabric/three-tier-architecture] The terms layer and tier are often used interchangeably, although *layer* is sometimes used to refer to a conceptual software logic structuring mechanism, while *tier* is used to refer to the physical hardware structuring mechanism for system infrastructure.
[src:datacenter-fabric/three-tier-architecture] In this usage, a three-layer solution could be deployed on a single tier, as in the case of an some database-centric architectures called RDBMS-only architecture or in personal workstations.
[src:datacenter-fabric/three-tier-architecture] The more usual convention is that the application layer (or service layer) is considered a sublayer of the business layer, typically encapsulating the application programming interface (API) definition surfacing the supported business functionality.
[src:datacenter-fabric/three-tier-architecture] The application/business layers can, in fact, be further subdivided to emphasize additional sublayers of distinct responsibility.
[src:datacenter-fabric/three-tier-architecture] For example, if the model–view–presenter pattern is used, the presenter sublayer might be used as an additional layer between the user interface layer and the business/application layer (as represented by the model sublayer).
[src:datacenter-fabric/three-tier-architecture] If the application architecture has no explicit distinction between the business layer and the presentation layer (i.e., the presentation layer is considered part of the business layer), then a traditional client-server (two-tier) model has been implemented.
[src:datacenter-fabric/three-tier-architecture] Some also identify a separate layer called the business infrastructure layer (BI), located between the business layer(s) and the infrastructure layer(s).
[src:datacenter-fabric/three-tier-architecture] It is also sometimes called the "low-level business layer" or the "business services layer".
[src:datacenter-fabric/three-tier-architecture] This layer is very general and can be used in several application tiers (e.g. a CurrencyConverter).
[src:datacenter-fabric/three-tier-architecture] The infrastructure layer can be partitioned into different levels (high-level or low-level technical services).
[src:datacenter-fabric/three-tier-architecture] Developers often focus on the persistence (data access) capabilities of the infrastructure layer and therefore only talk about the persistence layer or the data access layer (instead of an infrastructure layer or technical services layer).
[src:datacenter-fabric/three-tier-architecture] In other words, the other kind of technical services is not always explicitly thought of as part of any particular layer..
[src:datacenter-fabric/three-tier-architecture] The Data Access layer normally contains an object known as the Data Access Object (DAO).
[src:datacenter-fabric/three-tier-architecture] In a relaxed layered system, a layer can also depend on all of the layers below it and not merely the layer directly below it.
[src:datacenter-fabric/three-tier-architecture] The relaxed layered system has more couplings and is more difficult to change.
[src:datacenter-fabric/three-tier-architecture] Three-tier architecture is a client-server software architecture pattern in which the user interface (presentation), functional process logic ("business rules"), computer data storage and data access are developed and maintained as independent modules, most often on separate platforms.
[src:datacenter-fabric/three-tier-architecture] Donovan in Open Environment Corporation (OEC), a tools company he founded in Cambridge, Massachusetts..
[src:datacenter-fabric/three-tier-architecture] Apart from the usual advantages of modular software with well-defined interfaces, the three-tier architecture is intended to allow any of the three tiers to be upgraded or replaced independently in response to changes in requirements or technology.
[src:datacenter-fabric/three-tier-architecture] For example, a change of operating system in the *presentation tier* would only affect the user interface code.
[src:datacenter-fabric/three-tier-architecture] The middle tier may be multitiered itself (in which case the overall architecture is called an "*n*-tier architecture").
[src:datacenter-fabric/three-tier-architecture] A middle dynamic content processing and generation level application server (e.g., Symfony, Spring, ASP.NET, Django, Rails, Node.js).
[src:datacenter-fabric/three-tier-architecture] A back-end database or data store, comprising both data sets and the database management system software that manages and provides access to the data.
[src:datacenter-fabric/three-tier-architecture] Data transfer between tiers is part of the architecture.
[src:datacenter-fabric/three-tier-architecture] Protocols involved may include one or more of SNMP, CORBA, Java RMI, .NET Remoting, Windows Communication Foundation, sockets, UDP, web services or other standard or proprietary protocols.
[src:datacenter-fabric/three-tier-architecture] Often middleware is used to connect the separate tiers.
[src:datacenter-fabric/three-tier-architecture] Separate tiers often (but not necessarily) run on separate physical servers, and each tier may itself run on a cluster.
[src:datacenter-fabric/three-tier-architecture] The Application Response Measurement defines concepts and APIs for measuring performance and correlating transactions between tiers.
[src:datacenter-fabric/three-tier-architecture] Generally, the term "tiers" is used to describe physical distribution of components of a system on separate servers, computers, or networks (processing nodes).
[src:datacenter-fabric/three-tier-architecture] A three-tier architecture then will have three processing nodes.
[src:datacenter-fabric/three-tier-architecture] The term "layers" refers to a logical grouping of components which may or may not be physically located on one processing node.
